---
import LocationLayout from '../../layouts/LocationLayout.astro';
import { marsLocations } from '../../data/marsLocations';

const location = marsLocations.find(loc => loc.id === 'mawrth-vallis');
if (!location) {
  throw new Error('Mawrth Vallis location not found');
}
---

<LocationLayout title="Mawrth Vallis - Mars Location" location={location}>
  <!-- Hero Image Section -->
  <div class="mb-8">
    <div
      class="relative h-96 bg-gradient-to-r from-green-900 to-emerald-800 rounded-lg overflow-hidden"
    >
      <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-black/20"></div>
      <div class="absolute bottom-6 left-6 text-white">
        <p class="text-sm opacity-80">
          Layered phyllosilicate deposits revealing Mars' ancient water history
        </p>
        <p class="text-xs opacity-60">NASA/JPL/CRISM</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Overview Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">Overview</h2>
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
      <div class="lg:col-span-2">
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Mawrth Vallis represents one of Mars' most extraordinary repositories 
          of clay minerals, containing the highest abundance and diversity of 
          phyllosilicates discovered on the planet. This ancient valley system 
          preserves a thick, complex profile of clay minerals that tell the story 
          of extensive, long-term water activity during Mars' early history.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          The region harbors some of the largest phyllosilicate outcrops on Mars, 
          with up to 65% smectite clay content by volume in certain areas. These 
          layered deposits, formed through billions of years of water-rock 
          interactions, provide unparalleled insights into the environmental 
          conditions that may have supported life during Mars' Noachian period.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          Recent research has identified Mawrth Vallis as showcasing the highest 
          degree of aqueous alteration identified on Mars from orbit, making it 
          a unique window into the planet's ancient hydrogeologic history and 
          a compelling target for astrobiological investigations.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Quick Facts Sidebar -->
      <div class="bg-gray-800/50 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">Quick Facts</h3>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Location:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">Arabia Terra region</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Clay Content:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">Up to 65% smectites</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Formation Age:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">Noachian (>3.5 Ga)</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Mission Status:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">ExoMars backup landing site</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Key Feature:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">Highest Mars phyllosilicate abundance</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Phyllosilicate Deposits Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Phyllosilicate Treasure Trove: Mars' Clay Mineral Capital
    </h2>
    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-8 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        The phyllosilicate deposits at Mawrth Vallis exhibit a specific and 
        scientifically significant stratigraphic sequence that records changing 
        aqueous environments over geological time. This layered arrangement 
        provides crucial evidence for understanding how Mars' early climate 
        evolved and what conditions may have supported habitability.
      </p>
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">Lower Sequence</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Fe/Mg-smectite clay minerals</li>
            <li>• Formed via basalt alteration</li>
            <li>• Neutral pH water conditions</li>
            <li>• Extensive aqueous activity evidence</li>
            <li>• Ancient cratered terrain origin</li>
            <li>• Primary alteration products</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">Upper Sequence</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Hydrated silica deposits</li>
            <li>• Montmorillonite and kaolinite</li>
            <li>• Fe and Mg leaching evidence</li>
            <li>• Extended aqueous events</li>
            <li>• Chemical weathering products</li>
            <li>• Environmental transition markers</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Ancient Water Activity Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Evidence for Long-Lived Surface Water
    </h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-8">
      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-blue-900/50 to-blue-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-blue-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Aqueous Alteration Timeline
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          The thick stacks of clay minerals at Mawrth Vallis indicate chemical 
          alteration of massive rock sequences through interaction with liquid 
          water. This process required sustained water activity over periods 
          ranging from tens of thousands to millions of years, far exceeding 
          brief episodes of water activity.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          Multiple mineral horizons in the layered outcrops signify changing 
          geochemical environments, suggesting Mars experienced complex, 
          evolving water chemistry during its early history.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-green-900/50 to-green-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-green-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Environmental Conditions
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          Research suggests the Fe³⁺-rich smectites formed in warm surface 
          environments with mean annual temperatures of 5-10°C and seasonal 
          highs reaching 20-30°C. These conditions, combined with rainfall 
          and surface leaching, created ideal environments for clay formation.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          The formation timescale of tens to hundreds of thousands of years 
          indicates Mars maintained favorable conditions for extended periods 
          during the Noachian era.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
        Mineral Diversity and Significance
      </h3>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        CRISM spectral analysis has revealed an extraordinary diversity of 
        hydrated minerals at Mawrth Vallis, including aluminum smectite, 
        iron/magnesium smectite, hydrated silica, kaolinite group minerals, 
        and various iron oxides. This assemblage represents the most complete 
        record of aqueous mineral formation processes discovered on Mars.
      </p>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
        The presence of alunite, recently discovered in the region, provides 
        evidence for localized evaporative environments, adding another layer 
        of complexity to the area's aqueous history and suggesting diverse 
        microenvironments existed within the broader water-rich setting.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Astrobiological Potential Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Exceptional Astrobiological Potential
    </h2>
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
      <div class="lg:col-span-2">
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Phyllosilicate deposits represent some of the most promising 
          environments for the preservation of ancient life signatures. The 
          clay minerals at Mawrth Vallis have exceptional capability to preserve 
          organic compounds and potential biosignatures over geological 
          timescales, making them ideal targets for astrobiological investigations.
        </p>

        <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
          <div class="border-l-4 border-green-500 pl-4">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">
              Organic Preservation Potential
            </h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              Clay minerals easily preserve microscopic life on Earth, and 
              laboratory experiments suggest phyllosilicates could have served 
              as reaction centers for organic molecules, potentially playing 
              a role in the origin of life processes.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="border-l-4 border-blue-500 pl-4">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">
              Habitable Environment Indicators
            </h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              The layered phyllosilicate-rich outcrops record ancient active 
              chemical environments that could have supported habitable 
              conditions. The neutral pH conditions inferred from the mineral 
              assemblages would have been conducive to life processes.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="border-l-4 border-purple-500 pl-4">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">
              Biosignature Detection Target
            </h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              The ancient phyllosilicates could preserve evidence of ecosystems 
              over geologic timescales if life was present on ancient Mars. 
              The diverse mineral assemblages provide multiple targets for 
              biosignature detection strategies.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/50 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Habitability Factors
        </h3>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Water Activity:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">Extended</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">pH Conditions:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">Neutral</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Temperature:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">5-30°C range</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Preservation:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">Exceptional</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ExoMars Mission Connection Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      ExoMars Mission and Future Exploration
    </h2>
    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-8 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        Mawrth Vallis has been extensively evaluated as a prime landing site 
        for the European Space Agency's ExoMars mission. While Oxia Planum was 
        ultimately selected as the primary landing site, Mawrth Vallis remains 
        designated as a backup site and continues to be recognized as one of 
        Mars' most scientifically compelling exploration targets.
      </p>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
        <div class="border-l-4 border-yellow-500 pl-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">Mission Evaluation</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
            Mawrth Vallis was evaluated through multiple landing site selection 
            meetings, with two ellipses in the region proposed for both Mars2020 
            and ExoMars missions due to its exceptional scientific value.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="border-l-4 border-blue-500 pl-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">Scientific Objectives</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
            The region's rich geological record from Mars' wetter past makes 
            it ideal for ExoMars' goals of searching for signs of past life 
            and investigating ancient environmental conditions.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="border-l-4 border-purple-500 pl-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">2028 Mission Plans</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
            With ExoMars receiving additional funding and targeting a 2028 
            launch, Mawrth Vallis remains a high-priority backup target for 
            the mission's subsurface drilling and organic analysis capabilities.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Recent Research Discoveries Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      2024 Research Developments
    </h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-8">
      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-emerald-900/50 to-emerald-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-emerald-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Future In Situ Exploration Study
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          A comprehensive 2024 study published in Astrobiology magazine has 
          reinforced Mawrth Vallis as "A Fascinating Place for Future In Situ 
          Exploration." The research highlights key science targets and their 
          astrobiological interests within the proposed landing ellipses.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          The study describes opportunities for human exploration in terms of 
          both scientific discoveries and resource utilization, positioning 
          Mawrth Vallis as a cornerstone location for Mars exploration.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-teal-900/50 to-teal-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-teal-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Alunite Discovery
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          Recent discovery of alunite minerals in the candidate ExoMars landing 
          site provides evidence for localized evaporative environments. This 
          finding adds complexity to our understanding of the region's aqueous 
          history and suggests diverse water chemistry conditions existed.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          The presence of alunite indicates periods of concentrated brine 
          formation, potentially creating unique microenvironments for 
          extremophile-type organisms.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
        Advanced Spectral Analysis
      </h3>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Continued analysis using Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter's CRISM instrument 
        has revealed increasingly detailed views of the phyllosilicate 
        stratigraphy. These observations show that the complexity of mineral 
        layering exceeds initial estimates, suggesting even more extensive 
        and varied aqueous processes than previously recognized.
      </p>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
        The detailed mapping has identified specific targets within the region 
        that show the highest potential for organic preservation, guiding 
        future mission planning and landing site refinement.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Terraforming Assessment Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Terraforming Assessment
    </h2>
    <div
      class="bg-gradient-to-br from-green-900/30 to-green-800/20 p-8 rounded-lg border border-green-700/50"
    >
      <div class="flex items-center mb-6">
        <div
          class="w-12 h-12 bg-green-600 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center mr-4"
        >
          <span class="text-white font-bold text-xl">8</span>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white">
            High Terraforming Potential
          </h3>
          <p class="text-green-300">
            Exceptional clay resources and proven long-term water history
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Advantages</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Highest clay mineral abundance on Mars</li>
            <li>• Proven extended water activity history</li>
            <li>• Neutral pH soil conditions</li>
            <li>• Excellent agricultural potential</li>
            <li>• Natural water retention capabilities</li>
            <li>• Diverse mineral resources</li>
            <li>• Potential subsurface water access</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Challenges</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Limited current surface water</li>
            <li>• Dust accumulation concerns</li>
            <li>• Radiation exposure issues</li>
            <li>• Temperature extremes</li>
            <li>• Atmospheric pressure variations</li>
            <li>• Access to surrounding regions</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Scientific Significance Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Scientific Significance
    </h2>
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Mars Hydrogeologic Archive
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          Mawrth Vallis provides the most complete and accessible record of 
          Mars' ancient water activity available for study. The thick, layered 
          phyllosilicate deposits preserve a detailed archive of changing 
          environmental conditions during the planet's most habitable period, 
          offering insights crucial for understanding planetary climate evolution 
          and the potential for life beyond Earth.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Astrobiology Laboratory
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          The region serves as a natural laboratory for studying how life might 
          have originated and been preserved on Mars. The combination of 
          extended aqueous activity, diverse chemical environments, and 
          exceptional preservation potential makes Mawrth Vallis arguably the 
          most promising location for detecting evidence of ancient Martian life.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Future Exploration Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Future Exploration Roadmap
    </h2>
    <div
      class="bg-gradient-to-br from-purple-900/30 to-purple-800/20 p-8 rounded-lg border border-purple-700/50"
    >
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        Despite not being selected for the primary ExoMars landing site, 
        Mawrth Vallis remains one of the highest-priority targets for future 
        Mars exploration. Its unparalleled clay mineral deposits and 
        astrobiological potential ensure it will continue to be a cornerstone 
        location for understanding Mars' past and potential for life.
      </p>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">
            Exploration Priorities
          </h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Subsurface drilling to 2+ meters depth</li>
            <li>• Comprehensive organic compound analysis</li>
            <li>• Detailed phyllosilicate stratigraphy</li>
            <li>• Biosignature detection surveys</li>
            <li>• Ancient climate reconstruction</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">
            Technology Requirements
          </h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Advanced drilling capabilities</li>
            <li>• High-resolution spectroscopy</li>
            <li>• Sample caching systems</li>
            <li>• Long-range mobility platforms</li>
            <li>• Environmental monitoring suites</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- External Resources Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">Learn More</h2>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">NASA/ESA Resources</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://mars.nasa.gov/resources/636/clay-minerals-in-mawrth-vallis-region-of-mars/"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              NASA: Clay Minerals in Mawrth Vallis
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://science.nasa.gov/resource/chemical-alteration-by-water-mawrth-vallis/"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              NASA Science: Chemical Alteration Evidence
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">Scientific Papers</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://astrobiology.com/2024/11/mawrth-vallis-mars-a-fascinating-place-for-future-in-situ-exploration.html"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              2024 Astrobiology Study: Future Exploration
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7007808/"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Phyllosilicate Diversity and Aqueous Activity
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</LocationLayout>